$CATEGORY: CIT/M4/week-10/10-2-case-study-automated-medical-triage-what-failure-mode-was-to

::10.2-Q1:: A hospital deploys an AI-assisted triage system. When a patient arrives at the emergency department, the system reads the patient's age, reported symptoms, vital signs, and past diagnoses. It then outputs a priority score of 1 (critical), 2 (urgent), or 3 (non-urgent). A student observes the system in action and asks\: "What is the AI actually deciding?" Which answer is most accurate?
{
~The system diagnoses the patient's underlying medical condition so clinicians know what treatment to start immediately#The triage AI does not diagnose — it has no output for condition type. Diagnosis is a separate, downstream medical task; its single output is a priority score.
~The system recommends a specific treatment plan ranked by clinical urgency, so the care team knows what interventions to begin#Treatment planning is a separate downstream activity that happens after a doctor has seen the patient; the triage model only produces a queue priority score at entry.
=The system decides how long the patient can safely wait before seeing a doctor, by assigning a queue priority score#Correct — the AI's sole decision is the wait-time ranking encoded in the priority score (corpus §5.1).
~The system alerts the nearest doctor whenever a patient's vital signs fall outside normal ranges, triggering an immediate bedside response#Vital-sign alerting is a different class of clinical decision support; the triage AI scores the queue position at arrival, it does not generate real-time clinical alerts during the wait.
#### Tests LO1 — what the triage system does vs does not do (corpus §5.1). The stem surfaces the common misconception that the AI diagnoses or prescribes.
}

::10.2-Q2:: A post-deployment review of an AI triage system finds that, across all 12,000 patients processed in six months, the model's priority scores matched the eventual clinical outcome 88% of the time. When the same data is broken down by patient age, elderly patients (age 70+) were scored correctly only 69% of the time. Which statement best explains what this pattern illustrates about the failure mode?
{
=This is systematic under-scoring — a repeatable pattern concentrated in one patient group — not a random error spread evenly across all patients#Correct — a failure mode is defined by its repeatability and concentration in identifiable groups; 88% aggregate hiding 69% for elderly patients is the textbook example (corpus §5.2).
~This shows the system is performing within acceptable error tolerance because the aggregate accuracy of 88% exceeds most clinical benchmarks#Aggregate accuracy is precisely the metric that masks sub-group failure; 88% overall cannot validate performance for elderly patients experiencing 69% accuracy (corpus §5.4, Gap 1).
~This suggests the model was not given enough training data and needs a larger dataset to reduce all errors equally#Insufficient data volume is not the documented cause; the failure is a systematic bias in which patient groups were over- or under-represented in labelling, not data quantity.
~This indicates a random hardware or software fault that intermittently corrupts scores for any patient regardless of age or condition#A random fault would distribute errors across all groups without the age concentration; the pattern being limited to elderly patients is the defining feature of a failure mode, not a fault.
#### Tests LO2 — identifying systematic under-scoring and why it is not random (corpus §5.2). Correct answer is first, requiring learners to distinguish aggregate vs sub-group accuracy.
}

::10.2-Q3:: Six months after an AI triage system goes live, a quality team reviews incident logs. They find that individual nurses occasionally noted "patient looked worse than the score suggested" in informal shift handover notes, but no formal escalation ever reached the deployment team, and no sub-group accuracy analysis was ever run. Which form of "tolerated failure" does this best represent?
{
~Deliberately accepted — leaders reviewed the failure, judged the benefit-to-risk ratio acceptable, and made a documented decision to continue operating the system with a named decision-maker and a recorded outcome#Deliberate acceptance requires a conscious, documented decision by leaders who knew about the problem, including a formal risk assessment; nothing in the scenario shows that decision or that documentation was ever produced.
=Unknowingly sustained combined with "seen but dismissed" — the analysis that would have revealed the pattern was never run, and clinicians who noticed anomalies had no channel to escalate them#Correct — both the dominant forms are present\: the organisation never ran the sub-group analysis (unknowingly sustained) and clinicians noticed but could not escalate (seen but dismissed) (corpus §5.3).
~A one-off error caused by an atypical batch of patients, which the system will self-correct once it processes more data and updates its internal model weights#One-off errors and self-correction describe random noise; self-correction would require the model to receive feedback from patient outcomes, but triage models in this deployment had no such outcome feedback loop.
~A vendor software defect that the hospital had no means to detect or report without specialist tooling, and which would manifest as system errors rather than skewed scores#The failure mode is a model bias detectable with the hospital's own records; a vendor software defect would manifest as system errors or crashes, not as a systematic scoring pattern concentrated in identifiable patient groups.
#### Tests LO3 — why the failure persisted and which form of toleration applied (corpus §5.3). Correct answer is second; distractors target the "deliberate" misconception and random-noise framing.
}

::10.2-Q4:: Apply the Judgment Framework Question 2 (Q2)\: "Is the model's error visible before the harm occurs?" to the automated triage case. A patient scored as priority 3 (non-urgent) sits in the waiting room for two hours before a nurse notices she is deteriorating and calls an emergency response team. Which statement best describes what Q2 reveals about this scenario?
{
~Q2 is satisfied — the error is visible at the moment the nurse accepts the score, because the nurse can see both the AI output and the patient's physical appearance at triage#Visibility at the moment of score assignment means the nurse could theoretically catch the error then; but under automation bias and time pressure the score is accepted, not interrogated — and the patient's condition worsens invisibly in the queue. Q2 asks whether error is visible before harm, not theoretically observable (corpus §5.6).
~Q2 is not applicable here because the Judgment Framework is designed for automated decisions with immediate outputs, not time-delayed queue systems#The Framework explicitly applies to any high-stakes AI decision including queue-based systems; topic 9.8 and the corpus §5.6 apply Q2 directly to triage.
~Q2 is satisfied because the hospital's incident reporting system logs the deterioration event, making the error visible in the post-hoc audit#Post-hoc logging makes the error visible after harm has occurred, not before. Q2 specifically asks whether the error is visible before harm (corpus §5.6).
=Q2 is not satisfied — the error is invisible until after the harm, because the patient deteriorates in the waiting room before anyone connects the AI score to the worsening condition#Correct — the score is assigned, the patient enters the queue, and the error only becomes visible when the patient's clinical state deteriorates in the waiting room. By then, the harmful delay has already occurred (corpus §5.6).
#### Tests LO4 — applying Judgment Framework Q2 to the triage case (corpus §5.6). Correct answer is fourth (position 3). Distractors target the confusion between theoretical visibility and genuine pre-harm visibility.
}

::10.2-Q5:: A governance team is reviewing the triage AI deployment and wants to identify a control that would surface a sub-group failure mode WITHOUT requiring any person to proactively go looking for the problem. Which control best meets that requirement?
{
~A sub-group performance audit — run monthly, breaking model accuracy down by age band, shift, and symptom entry method, reviewed by a named role outside the deployment team#A sub-group audit would reveal the failure mode but requires a named human to schedule and execute the analysis each month; it is event-independent and not self-triggering (corpus §5.7, Control 1).
=A deterioration-contradiction alert — a software rule that automatically flags for review any AI "non-urgent" score when the patient clinically deteriorates within 120 minutes of queue assignment#Correct — the alert fires automatically whenever the contradiction occurs, making the pattern visible without anyone having to actively look. Over dozens of events, the sub-group concentration becomes statistically clear (corpus §5.7, Control 2).
~A mandatory written justification requirement whenever a clinician overrides the AI score, reviewed weekly by the department manager to identify patterns in clinician disagreement#Requiring override justifications addresses Gap 3 (override accountability) but only surfaces failure when someone actively overrides the score; it cannot detect the cases where the AI score is silently accepted and the patient waits unquestioned.
~A vendor-supplied accuracy dashboard displaying the model's rolling 30-day aggregate accuracy, checked monthly by the deployment team against a defined performance threshold#A rolling aggregate dashboard is precisely the metric that hides sub-group failure; real-world data showed 87% overall accuracy coexisting with 70% accuracy for elderly patients, meaning the dashboard would report no alarm (corpus §5.4, Gap 1).
#### Tests LO5 — distinguishing the automated detection control (deterioration-contradiction alert) from the scheduled analysis control (sub-group audit) (corpus §5.7). Correct answer is second.
}

::10.2-Q6:: A data analyst on a hospital quality team looks at six months of AI triage records. She groups patients by age band and calculates the percentage of cases where the AI's priority score matched the eventual clinical outcome for each group. She discovers that patients aged 75+ were correctly scored only 66% of the time, compared to 91% for patients under 60. According to the six-step diagnostic procedure, which step is the analyst performing?
{
~Step 1 — Describing the system's decision in one sentence, covering inputs, outputs, and the consequence the output triggers for each patient in the queue#Step 1 asks for a concise description of the system before any data work begins; the analyst in this scenario is already past system description and is deep into measuring accuracy across patient categories.
~Step 4 — Applying Q1, Q2, and Q3 from the Judgment Framework to assess the cost, visibility, and human-checkpoint quality of the AI's decisions#Step 4 is the Judgment Framework application (Q1/Q2/Q3); the analyst is not weighing decision stakes or evaluating human oversight checkpoints — she is measuring accuracy broken down by patient category.
~Step 5 — Identifying the governance gap type by choosing from evaluation design, checkpoint frequency, override accountability, or alert threshold#Step 5 is the gap classification step, which comes after the failure has been identified; the analyst is still producing the accuracy evidence that would eventually support that classification, not naming the gap yet.
=Step 3 — Asking whether the failure was visible with existing data, by demonstrating that the sub-group breakdown could be derived from records the organisation already held#Correct — Step 3 asks\: "Was the failure visible with existing data?" The analyst is doing exactly that — running the analysis on existing records to show the failure was detectable all along (corpus §6, Step 3).
#### Tests LO6 — recognising the six-step diagnostic step being performed (corpus §6). Correct answer is fourth. Distractors are plausible adjacent steps that learners might confuse.
}
